      <hedline>
        <hl1>Who's Divisive?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arthur R Yeager letter, commenting on August 19 article, rejects Gov George Bush's complaint about Vice Pres Al Gore's divisiveness until he explains how he intends to control excesses of Republican Party's contentious leadership</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''After Convention, Bush Chides Gore for Divisive Tone'' (front page, Aug. 19):</p>
        <p>A deaf ear must be turned to George W. Bush's complaint about Al Gore's divisiveness until the Texas governor explains just how he intends to control the excesses of his own party's contentious leadership.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''After Convention, Bush Chides Gore for Divisive Tone'' (front page, Aug. 19):</p>
        <p>A deaf ear must be turned to George W. Bush's complaint about Al Gore's divisiveness until the Texas governor explains just how he intends to control the excesses of his own party's contentious leadership.</p>
        <p>Probably the most malicious, divisive action of the last century was the impeachment of President Clinton by House Republicans. Motivated by anger, hatred and distrust, Representatives Henry J. Hyde, Bob Barr, Dick Armey, Tom DeLay, the House managers and others finger-pointed, politicized and blamed the president.</p>
        <p>To be credible in his call for civility, Mr. Bush must make clear whether he now supports the House leadership's action and what role they might play in a Bush administration.</p>
        <p>ARTHUR L. YEAGER  Edison, N.J., Aug. 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
